# React Compiler first (React 19)

- **Default**: write code that is naturally compiler-friendly; assume React Compiler will optimize.
- **Only add `useMemo` / `useCallback`** after profiling or when you have a proven referential-stability requirement.

## Prefer this
- **Stable component boundaries**: keep components pure; derive values from props/state without mutating inputs.
- **Compute inline** when cheap; extract helpers when it improves clarity.
- **Use `memo` sparingly**; prefer splitting components over heavy memoization.
- **Component props**: prefer `interface Props {}` over inline parameter types.

## Reach for `useMemo` / `useCallback` only when
- Passing callbacks/objects to **non-compiler-aware** libs that rely on referential equality
- A dependency causes **observable re-renders** that you can’t fix by refactoring

### Example

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD: simple, compiler-friendly
interface RowProps {
  item: Item;
  onSelect: (id: string) => void;
}

function Row({ item, onSelect }: RowProps) {
  return <button onClick={() => onSelect(item.id)}>{item.name}</button>;
}
```

